Forecasting Earthquakes

This data is from the National Earthquake Information Center NEIC which is the US archive for earthquake information. This forecast solely involves data from 1981 and 2016. This closereading is meant for the general public

Section 1:Forecasting Earthquakes

It is commonly known that sismic activity is unpredictable and there is not enough current evidence to establish that earthquakes happen at a specific place, climate or time. We currently only predict their long-term occurence and the general area of sismic activity leaving us without much preparation for the eventually of a dangerous earthquake.

I will be attempting to forecast the magnitude and prevalence of these earthquakes in the US with data from the NEIC by modeling the shape and direction of the data.

Mortality: Earthquakes kill around 360 people every year and injure thousands.

Section 2: Earthquakes Across Time

According to the data, Earthquakes have been occurring pretty regularly since 1981, with a relatively stable monthly magnitude on average.

However, there seems to be no common knowledge and limited literature on the predictable trends or seasonal patterns of earthquakes. Such knowledge would help us take proactive measures to maximise safety and potentially decrease the US earthquake mortality int he future.

Section 4: Is there such a thing as Earthquake season?

While we do not currently have evidence to establish that earthquakes happen in any specific place, time or conditions, recent research is exploring some potentially significant inrcreases in the magnitude and prevalence of earthquakes in areas of the Northern hemisphere like the US.
